CatDescriptText: Cutline of related image published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, August 18, 1951, pg. 1, reads: "PROTEST WEBSTER AVENUE KILLINGS - Two deaths in less than four weeks proved too much for the Webster Avenue residents. They demanded Tuesday that the city take steps to put up stop signs and lights.  Left: Youngsters display signs in orderly fashion while crowd forms barrier to keep truck and cars from passing..."
TitMainTitle: Crowd of teenagers, women, and men, including police officer, and possibly Robert "Pappy" William on right, gathered in front of house with random patterned Insulbrick, numbered 2801, protesting lack of signs, patrol, and lights on Webster Avenue, Hill District
